      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "176e0e93_a25613c4",
      "file_path": "main/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/pap/main/rest/PolicyStatusProvider.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 99,
      "message": "I see, so if it's not a valid regex, then the code assumes it's really just a plain name.  That seems like it could lead to unexpected results for the client.\n\nAdding a flag to the API would eliminate the ambiguity - if the client says it's a regex, then it must be a valid regex, and if the client does not specify that it's a regex, then we would do an exact match",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2021-04-27 14:53:48.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "05f7dfce_b1fdd1dd",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "aa6ee638_84cd6760",
      "file_path": "main/src/test/java/org/onap/policy/pap/main/rest/TestPolicyStatusProvider.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 244,
      "message": "this still doesn't make sense.  The compiler should know which getStatus() to invoke when these are used:\n\n  getStatus() - compiler should invoke the zero-argument method\n  getStatus(any()) - compiler should invoke the one-argument method\n\nthere should be no ambiguity.  Did you try it?",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2021-04-27 14:53:48.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "eceab011_053e1677",
      "unresolved": true
    },
