    {
      "id": "97b190f3_0930dd46",
      "file_path": "main/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/pap/main/rest/PolicyStatusControllerV1.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 142,
      "message": "Ups, forget about what I said about, it is not to the path variable, just for the parameter.\nfor the path one regex \"n?ame\" can not be passed. It is ok only for parameters",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7662,
        "name": "Arkadiusz Adamski",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "aadamski@est.tech",
        "username": "arkadiusz.adamski"
      },
      "updated": "2021-04-29 10:05:11.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "f99f986f_b59ae4d3",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "4e4ff924_fcbbf42c",
      "file_path": "main/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/pap/main/rest/PolicyStatusControllerV1.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 142,
      "message": "I'm OK saying that a client has to url-encode the URL if the policy \"name\" contains regex characters - that's generally how things work with other web sites.  On the other hand, we could instead add the regex pattern as an optional QueryParam for the \"policies/deployed\" api.  That might make more sense as it would behave like a filtering parameter, which is also a common strategy.\n\nPersonally, I tend to like the latter, as it's common practice AND it may absolve the client of having to URL-encode the value.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2021-04-29 13:27:44.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "97b190f3_0930dd46",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "7881e2f6_b491b47c",
      "file_path": "main/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/pap/main/rest/PolicyStatusControllerV1.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 142,
      "message": "I think that's better, so the code should move to the \"policies/deployed\" URL endpoint, the previous method, instead of here \"policies/deployed/{name}\", something sort of \"policies/deployed?regex=^H[A-Z]+\" would be OK vs. something like \"policies/deployed/^H[A-Z]?regex=true\" which I was having trouble with.   Point being, a policy-name regex should not be part of the path url.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 477,
        "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
        "username": "jhh"
      },
      "updated": "2021-04-29 13:54:34.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "4e4ff924_fcbbf42c",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "aab7aaf7_42abc456",
      "file_path": "main/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/pap/main/rest/PolicyStatusControllerV1.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 142,
      "message": "OK, at the moment I treat empty string in:\npolicies/deployed?regex=\nas valid regex. So it will match nothing. This is something that we want, or should I treat the same as\npolicies/deployed\n?",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 7662,
        "name": "Arkadiusz Adamski",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "aadamski@est.tech",
        "username": "arkadiusz.adamski"
      },
      "updated": "2021-04-29 15:22:18.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "7881e2f6_b491b47c",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "0044dc10_7a8a0608",
      "file_path": "main/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/pap/main/rest/PolicyStatusControllerV1.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 142,
      "message": "I think it would be better to be strict with the users, and return an error if regex is passed as empty.   The way that you have it makes sense too, but I think is better to deny the request so not to create bad habits on clients.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 477,
        "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
        "username": "jhh"
      },
      "updated": "2021-04-29 15:44:22.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "aab7aaf7_42abc456",
      "unresolved": true
    },
